title: May National REV UP Call: Voter Access in Jails, Congregate Settings

sponsor.name: REV UP, American Association of People with Disabilities (AAPD)

description:
National REV UP Meetings are designed to keep you up-to-date and engaged. Each call kicks off with important updates, like upcoming funding opportunities or timely policy actions. Then, we dive into a featured discussion topic, often with an expert guest speaker. 

To make the most of our time together, you'll also join small breakout groups where you can share ideas, strategize, and learn with others.

May Discussion Topic: Expanding voting access and civics education for incarcerated people

People who are incarcerated and in other congregate settings face unique challenges when voting, and even more so when they have a disability. During this session, we’ll be joined by a group of community and advocacy organizations who have been working in Tennessee to support hundreds of eligible incarcerated and disabled incarcerated voters to understand their voting rights, engage in civics education, and successfully cast their ballots. We’ll also encourage attendees to explore how lessons learned from voting in jails and prisons can be used to expand voting access in any congregate settings where members of the disability community may reside such as nursing homes and assisted living facilities.

title: Team ENOUGH Welcome Session (For Young People Under 26)
description:
Are you a young person between 13 and 25 years old who is interested in taking action around preventing gun violence? Join us for our Team ENOUGH welcome session to learn more about the different ways you can engage.

Team ENOUGH is a youth-led program whose mission is to educate young voices about gun violence and mobilize them to take meaningful action against it. Supported by Brady United, we harness the expertise and experience of today’s youth to advance our intersectional work across the country.

Led by an Executive Council, comprised of students just like us, we believe that diversity is a strength, and that only when everyone has a seat at the table can we build an effective movement to prevent all gun violence in all communities.

For us, preventing gun violence not only requires regulating access to firearms but also addressing how systemic racism and environmental factors cause this form of bloodshed to run especially rampant in communities of color. You cannot talk about gun violence without talking about police brutality, white supremacy, the broken criminal justice system, poverty, homophobia, access to affordable housing, or the often barriers separating disadvantaged populations from physical and mental healthcare.

So if you share this belief, join us for our Team ENOUGH welcome session and become part of the movement to end gun violence in our lifetime.

title: Stop Microplastics Now! Campaign Meeting
description:
**Food & Water Action has launched a new campaign against microplastics, the tiny plastic particles that are now pervasive in our food and water.**

Last year, we filed a legal petition with the EPA urging the agency to monitor microplastics as a water contaminant. Our Stop Microplastics Now! Campaign aims to force the agency to act by getting state governors to join our petition. This is an important way to for state leaders to force the federal government to protect our water. 

On this campaign action call, we will dig deeper into the steps we can take to ensure seven governors join our petition to force the EPA to act. **Join us to learn what you can do in your community to make a big impact nationwide on protecting our drinking water!**

Here’s what you’ll learn:

Part One: The Power of Storytelling: Learn how to combine field-tested messages with your own personal experience to create a powerful story that can inspire change.

Part Two: The Power of Voice: Learn how to deliver your message effectively at a public meeting or one-on-one with legislators or journalists.

Part Three: The Power of Presence: Learn how local and state government works when you’re advocating for policy change.

You can take this workshop free of charge - but it costs us $25/per person to offer it. If you’d like to make a donation to cover all or part of our costs, a donation link will be shared with you after you register.

description:
Hello, friend. As we enter the first 100 days of Trump 2.0, we need to gather for mutual support and collective action, because we together, we can help shape the road ahead.

Join us in building resilient communities that fight for our freedoms, families and future.

Right now, you may be feeling defiant, angry, fearful or even despairing. One of the most important revelations of this time is that, whatever we may feel, we are not alone. 

_Building our community is one of the strongest actions we can take to ultimately stop authoritarianism, and being together – helps._

**Join our in-person Sunday afternoon meetings in Manhattan to connect the dots as we connect with each other.**

**Wherever you are at, there is something powerful you can do – even simply showing up. Simply coming to a community meeting.**

Since 11/5, we've been building our action plan for where we go from here. What it can look like to effectively push back on Trump 2.0.

At these open house gatherings, you'll learn:

-Helpful coping skills

-Resources for understanding where we're at

-Effective actions that can slow or stop Trump's harms, _just as we have successfully done before_

We'll always meet in Manhattan, but you will receive each week's specific location by email and/or text/phone a day or two in advance.

Come to one session or keep coming to all. Everyone who loves our freedoms, our democracy, and each other are welcome.

Join us and see why showing up means _everything_ now.

The Target Majority NYC Core Team

Civic Sundays LA is having a Truth Bomb Briefing, led by Johanna Siegmann, previewing a new way of communicating that meets the moment.  This is a virtual event and will be held over Zoom on alternating Fridays at 2pm PT/ 5pm ET.

TRUTH BOMBS

Welcome to the Opposition!

Marc Elias urges us to be the Opposition, so that’s what we will be.
Timothy Snyder urges us to cultivate and amplify new communication methods and messengers, and that’s what this is!
 
It’s time for a radical change to the way we think of politics, because politics has changed radically. THEY have adapted. We continue to be fractured, and our messaging is scattered. And we continue to value our individuality over discipline, which carries a heavy political cost.
 
We need to address all that. 
 
Although the 2024 election loss was due to many real issues, king of them all was disinformation. They basically won with memes.

In this one-hour zoom, we will discuss Truth Bombs – a simple new, non-confrontational, social-media-based weapon to add to our arsenal; we’ll talk about what Truth Bombs are, who creates them, where and how to deploy them, who they’re aimed at, and what we hope to achieve with them.
 
And we will all learn the raw power of “less is more”.

We are the Opposition and we are not ceding ONE INCH!!

Thanks for showing up and doing something!

title: Team ENOUGH Welcome Session (For Young People Under 26)
description:
Are you a young person between 13 and 25 years old who is interested in taking action around preventing gun violence? Join us for our Team ENOUGH welcome session to learn more about the different ways you can engage.

Team ENOUGH is a youth-led program whose mission is to educate young voices about gun violence and mobilize them to take meaningful action against it. Supported by Brady United, we harness the expertise and experience of today’s youth to advance our intersectional work across the country.

Led by an Executive Council, comprised of students just like us, we believe that diversity is a strength, and that only when everyone has a seat at the table can we build an effective movement to prevent all gun violence in all communities.

For us, preventing gun violence not only requires regulating access to firearms but also addressing how systemic racism and environmental factors cause this form of bloodshed to run especially rampant in communities of color. You cannot talk about gun violence without talking about police brutality, white supremacy, the broken criminal justice system, poverty, homophobia, access to affordable housing, or the often barriers separating disadvantaged populations from physical and mental healthcare.

So if you share this belief, join us for our Team ENOUGH welcome session and become part of the movement to end gun violence in our lifetime.

Are you a young person between 13 and 25 years old who is interested in taking action around preventing gun violence? Join us for our Team ENOUGH welcome session to learn more about the different ways you can engage.

Team ENOUGH is a youth-led program whose mission is to educate young voices about gun violence and mobilize them to take meaningful action against it. Supported by Brady United, we harness the expertise and experience of today’s youth to advance our intersectional work across the country.

Led by an Executive Council, comprised of students just like us, we believe that diversity is a strength, and that only when everyone has a seat at the table can we build an effective movement to prevent all gun violence in all communities.

For us, preventing gun violence not only requires regulating access to firearms but also addressing how systemic racism and environmental factors cause this form of bloodshed to run especially rampant in communities of color. You cannot talk about gun violence without talking about police brutality, white supremacy, the broken criminal justice system, poverty, homophobia, access to affordable housing, or the often barriers separating disadvantaged populations from physical and mental healthcare.

So if you share this belief, join us for our Team ENOUGH welcome session and become part of the movement to end gun violence in our lifetime.

title: INDIANA: Rapid Response for Our Freedoms
description:
Are you alarmed by the far-right's **relentless push to dismantle our democracy** and undermine our future? The *time to act is now*—your voice and involvement are vital in this critical moment.

Together, we have the power to **resist this dangerous agenda** that seeks to replace our democracy with authoritarian rule. By organizing, mobilizing, and holding leaders accountable, we can **protect the rights, freedoms, and values that define America.**

Join us for **"Rapid Response for Our Freedoms,"** a crucial event where we **stand as one to defend democracy**, *uphold the rule of law,* and safeguard the **rights and freedoms we all hold dear.** 

*This is our moment to rise up* for an America that includes everyone when we say *"liberty and justice for all," * not just the wealthy and powerful.

### Goals of the Event:

-To **mobilize and activate** a network of people ready to take **immediate, strategic action** to defend our *rights, freedoms, the rule of law, and democracy.*

-To **educate and inform** participants about current *authoritarian threats, legal overreach, and* **coordinated attacks on our freedoms.**

-To share **concrete tools, tactics, and next steps** that individuals and groups can take in their communities to *push back.*

-To build a **connected movement** rooted in *collective power, solidarity, and a shared vision of justice and equality for all*—not just the wealthy, powerful, or those with privilege.

### What You'll Take Away: 

-A **clear understanding** of the threats we face—and the *power we have to overcome them.*

-**Action steps** you can take *immediately* to protect our rights, freedoms, the rule of law, and democracy.

-**Resources** for organizing *locally and nationally* with other committed members of People Power United.

-A **renewed sense of purpose, community, and hope**—knowing *you're not alone* in this fight.

The strength of **people power is unstoppable**—together, *we can and will make a difference.*

At **People Power United**, we believe in **progress** and the strength of **collective action**. Together, we can push back against extremism and **build a brighter future.** Join us in the fight for **Freedom over Fascism** and help *amplify the power of people* to shape our democracy!

title: Food Scraps Collection: Encino Farmers' Market
description:
As a volunteer, you’ll be right in the action, collecting food scraps from market-goers—the first step in a crucial process that turns waste into nutrient-rich compost. These scraps, gathered at local markets, are then processed at nearby green parks or gardens. Throughout your shift, you'll be guided by an experienced LA Compost staff member, who will act as your Compost Manager, offering insights and helping you share the benefits of composting with the public. The best part is that during your volunteer shift, you can take some time to shop at the market. Join us and be part of the composting movement that's transforming LA—one food scrap at a time!

#### ABOUT ACTIVITY:
As a volunteer, you’ll play a hands-on role in guiding market-goers through composting, ensuring their food scraps are clean of stickers, compostable, and ready to be turned into nutrient-rich compost. You’ll monitor for contamination, assist with tracking data, and serve as a friendly, welcoming host to our composting community. 

#### MORE INFO: 
* You'll be stationed at the LA Compost booth under a pop-up canopy within the farmers' market. There will also be seating available.
* You may be asked to assist with moving filled bins of material weighing 60+ pounds. We always offer team lifts; you will never be asked to lift bins if you prefer not to.
* No prior composting experience is needed; everyone is welcome!
* Bathrooms are accessible.
* If you sign up, please show up! We rely on volunteers like you to achieve our mission.  
* We’ll follow up with details via email, so be sure to provide your best contact email when signing up.

#### AGE REQUIREMENT:
This volunteer activity is best suited for volunteers aged 16 and up. Minors under 16 should come accompanied by a parent or guardian unless other arrangements are made. Contact ashleigh@lacompost.org for more information.

#### IMPORTANT: VOLUNTEER WAIVER
Please make sure you have signed the volunteer waiver. 
Access the e-wavier at https://www.lacompost.org/waiver

title: Team ENOUGH Welcome Session (For Young People Under 26)
description:
Are you a young person between 13 and 25 years old who is interested in taking action around preventing gun violence? Join us for our Team ENOUGH welcome session to learn more about the different ways you can engage.

Team ENOUGH is a youth-led program whose mission is to educate young voices about gun violence and mobilize them to take meaningful action against it. Supported by Brady United, we harness the expertise and experience of today’s youth to advance our intersectional work across the country.

Led by an Executive Council, comprised of students just like us, we believe that diversity is a strength, and that only when everyone has a seat at the table can we build an effective movement to prevent all gun violence in all communities.

For us, preventing gun violence not only requires regulating access to firearms but also addressing how systemic racism and environmental factors cause this form of bloodshed to run especially rampant in communities of color. You cannot talk about gun violence without talking about police brutality, white supremacy, the broken criminal justice system, poverty, homophobia, access to affordable housing, or the often barriers separating disadvantaged populations from physical and mental healthcare.

So if you share this belief, join us for our Team ENOUGH welcome session and become part of the movement to end gun violence in our lifetime.

title: Letter Carriers’ Stamp Out Hunger® Food Drive, hosted by the USPS & Partners
description:
Use the provided bag - ask your local Post Office - and fill it with food to be picked up. 

The 33rd Annual Letter Carriers’ 
Stamp Out Hunger® Food Drive 

https://www.nalc.org/community-service/food-drive

Food Drive History
The NALC National Food Drive is the outgrowth of a tradition of community service exhibited repeatedly by members of the letter carriers union over the years. These carriers, who go into neighborhoods in every town six days a week, have always been involved when something needed to be done, whether it be collecting funds for a charity like the Muscular Dystrophy Association, watching over the elderly through the Carrier Alert program, assisting the American Red Cross during times of disaster, or rescuing victims of fires, crime, and other mishaps.

For many years, a number of branches had collected food for the needy as part of their community service effort.

The national, coordinated effort by the NALC to help fight hunger in America grew out of discussions in 1991 by a number of leaders at the time, including NALC President Vincent R. Sombrotto, AFL-CIO Community Services Director Joseph Velasquez and Postmaster General Anthony Frank. A pilot drive was held in 10 cities in October of 1991, and it proved so successful that work began immediately on making it a nationwide effort.

Input from food banks and pantries suggested that late spring would be the best time since by then most food banks in the country start running out of donations received during the Thanksgiving and Christmas holiday periods.

A revamped drive was organized for May 15, 1993—the second Saturday in May—with a goal of having at least one NALC branch in each of the 50 states participating. The result was astounding. More than 11 million pounds of food was collected—a one-day record in the United States—involving more than 220 union branches.

From Alaska to Florida and Maine to Hawaii, letter carriers did double duty—delivering mail and picking up donations. It just grew and grew from that point.

In 2010, the food drive surpassed the 1 billion pound park in total food collected over its history.

title: 2025 Legislative Review with Representative Anna V. Eskamani
description:
**Join State Representative Anna V. Eskamani, PhD, for a post-session virtual review of the 2025 Legislative Session on Monday, May 19th from 6:00pm to 7:30pm.**

The Florida Legislative Session is the 60-day state lawmaking period of the year, expected to end this year on Friday, May 2nd. As such, we want to make sure you have the insights you need to be informed and stay engaged no matter where you live in the Sunshine State.

During our program, we'll cover a host of issues ranging from attacks on immigrant, LGBTQ+ and worker rights to gun laws, voting rights, property insurance, the state budget, and more. Empower yourselves and others with the latest policy updates delivered directly from Rep. Eskamani!

Closed captions will be available in English. This event will be live-streamed on Facebook and available on Zoom by RSVP with the form here.

*Do you want to stay up to date between now and then? Sign up here for our legislative newsletter: www.annaforflorida.com/legislativeupdate.*
